SIMPLE: grease
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Grease
<hw>Grease</hw> <pr>(gr⟦emac⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>grese</ets>, <ets>grece</ets>, F. <ets>graisse</ets>; akin to
<ets>gras</ets> fat, greasy, fr. LL. <ets>grassus</ets> thick, fat,
gross, L. <ets>crassus</ets>. Cf. <er>Crass</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Animal fat, as tallow or lard, especially when in a soft state;
oily or unctuous matter of any kind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Far.)</fld> <def>An inflammation of a horse's
heels, suspending the ordinary greasy secretion of the part, and
producing dryness and scurfiness, followed by cracks, ulceration, and
fungous excrescences.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Grease bush</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>Same as
<cref>Grease wood</cref> (below).</cd> -- <col><b>Grease moth</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a pyralid moth (<spn>Aglossa pinguinalis</spn>)
whose larva eats greasy cloth, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Grease
wood</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a scraggy, stunted, and somewhat
prickly shrub (<spn>Sarcobatus vermiculatus</spn>) of the Spinach
family, very abundant in alkaline valleys from the upper Missouri to
California. The name is also applied to other plants of the same family,
as several species of <gen>Atriplex</gen> and
<gen>Obione</gen>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grease</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Grease
<hw>Grease</hw> <pr>(gr⟦emac⟧z <it>or</it> gr⟦emac⟧s; 277)</pr>, <pos>v.
t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Greased</conjf>
<pr>(gr⟦emac⟧zd <it>or</it> gr⟦emac⟧sd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Greasing</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To smear, anoint, or daub, with grease or fat; to
lubricate; <as>as, to grease the wheels of a wagon</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bribe; to corrupt with presents.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>greased</qex> advocate that grinds the poor.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cheat or cozen; to overreach.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Far.)</fld> <def>To affect (a horse) with grease,
the disease.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To grease in the hand</b></col>, <col><b>To grease
the hand</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to corrupt by bribes.</cd>
<rj><au>Usher.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>greaseball</ent>⟦br⟧
